Introduction
As women continue to make remarkable strides toward equality, they are constantly being judged, they are constantly being valued based on their appearance. Despite the advancements in equality, power, and position, women still face obstacles such as being valued based on their physical appearance and ability to become fertile. The stigma arose in the 1900s, when the Beauty Myth was prevalent. According to the author, Naomi Wolf, the beauty myth is not solely based on beauty, but also “it is composed of emotional distance, politics, finance, and sexual repression” (Wolf 1991). The beauty myth focused so much on women’s appearance for advancement in gender hierarchy, not just for respect within the community, but also for political advancement. Men also faced social pressure to pursue a ‘beautiful’ woman to gain more political power. According to Wolf (1991), “strong men battle for beautiful women, and beautiful women are more reproductively successful.” Essentially, men and women were both defined by women’s beauty. 
As we learned in class, the collective conscious is an unspoken, unwritten, set of rules and standards that society unknowingly follows. Each individual’s collective conscious, during the beauty myth period, focused so evidently on beauty and appearance. There was so much pressure on both genders to be physically attractive. According to Wolf, “many [women] are ashamed to admit that such trivial concerns to do with physical appearance, bodies, faces, hair, clothes – matter so much” (1991). Even though women are becoming more powerful within society, their collective conscious will always remind them that there is an unspoken expectation to be beautiful. Insecurities, mental illnesses, and even health issues became more extensive to women. There was a high standard to fit in with society for women, and women worked hard to be within these irrational standards. 
	Did you know that “More than 1 million American teenagers and preteens live with an eating disorder—about 3 percent of that population” (Cooperman 2009)? Currently, in the United States, eating disorders have become increasingly popular. Interestingly enough, it is more common in women than in men. So, is it possible that the beauty myth from the 1900s, that focused so highly on women’s physical attraction for political advancement acted as a precursor to current eating disorders? 
What is the Beauty Myth? 
	Naomi Wolf, author of “The Beauty Myth”, discusses the importance of the beauty myth stigma and defines the political movement. As women socially and politically advance within society, Wolf elucidates the decline in mental health. Women in society were constantly being compared to old photographs of what society considered beautiful women. In order to meet society’s expectations, women were constantly focusing on their exterior. How women portrayed themselves to society was crucial for political advancement for both themselves and for the men in society. There were unspoken expectations for men to pursue beautiful women in order to become more politically powerful. How each gender was perceived by society mattered. These irrational standards for physical attraction increased numerous kinds of mental illnesses and, more importantly, eating disorders. 
	According to Wolf, “During the past decade, women breached the power; meanwhile, eating disorders rose exponentially and cosmetic surgery became the fastest growing medical specialty” (1991). During the rise of feminism and the fight for equality, women believed that a necessity that contributes to political power was to be beautiful. Back then, women were constantly forced to look at photographs of provocative, thin women. Because of the beauty stigma, women constantly would strive to look just like these provocative women. It was important to have a youthful face, but not too youthful, and to be skinny. It was just as important to dress up appropriately to society’s standards. Women were defined not only by physical looks, but also by the clothing that they chose to wear. Women’s body shape should be the same as the women in the photographs, which led to unnecessary dieting. The pressure for women to appropriately portray themselves to society was uncanny and unfair. Women were vulnerable to outside approval which, in turn, consequently led to self-esteem issues, mental disorders, and most importantly eating disorders. 
What is an Eating Disorder?
 What exactly is an eating disorder? An eating disorder can be defined as “...medically and psychiatrically recognized illnesses...they are complex conditions involving mental, physical, and social issues” (Cooperman 2009). An eating disorder is serious and potentially fatal. Eating disorders are so important to understand because they encompass both unhealthy eating behaviors and also mental illnesses. In order to be diagnosed with an eating disorder, the individual must have serious disturbances in their eating behavior. This can include an extreme or unhealthy reduction of food intake, severe over-eating, or feelings of distress or extreme concern about body shape or weight (Cooperman 2009). 
Eating disorders begin when an individual is unhappy with their appearance. There are numerous types of eating disorders such as anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, and binge-eating disorder. Each disorder is serious and can become fatal because of the biological and physical detrimental effects.  For example, anorexia nervosa is the most prevalent eating disorder. Anorexia nervosa includes feelings of low self-esteem, lack of eating, and an intense fear of gaining weight. Due to this fear of gaining weight, individuals are usually below the healthy body mass index average. Body Mass Index (B.M.I) is defined by the person’s weight in comparison to their height. Unfortunately, being below the BMI average indicates lack of healthy eating and lack of healthy physical involvement. Without proper eating styles, the individual will lack the proper nutrients that enable the body to function properly. Without appropriate physical activity, the individual will lack metabolic movement, and the body will become slower in almost every anatomical aspect. The second most common eating disorder is bulimia nervosa. This eating disorder isn’t as serious as anorexia nervosa, but it still can become unhealthy. Bulimia Nervosa can be triggered by life’s stressors. An individual with bulimia nervosa will binge-eat for an unhealthy period of time, and then later, want to reverse the effects of eating too much. This individual will purge the calories that they just ate by either self-inducing vomit or by excess exercise. This purging stage can become dangerous for the individual but is a hard action to treat due to the positive emotional effects that the reversal can have on the individual. The individual will have these positive emotions because they feel proud that they reversed the caloric gain. An individual with bulimia nervosa likes feeling in control of their purge making this disorder hard to treat. (Cooperman 2009) 
Lastly, the third most common eating disorder is binge-eating. Unlike the other two disorders, binge-eating does not correlate with weight-loss. These individuals will eat an excessive amount but will not purge their weight. Interestingly, despite the individual’s lack of reversal of the caloric intake, these individuals will still have low self-esteem. Each eating disorder has one thing in common and that is low self-esteem and / or poor image issues. Statistically, women are more prone to eating disorders than men. So, did the beauty myth stigma leave such a detrimental impact that still effects millions of women today? 
Beauty Myth and Eating disorders
 	Did you know that at least, approximately, 7 million women are diagnosed with an eating disorder (Kramer 2021)? During the beauty myth stigma time period, women constantly compare themselves to photogprahs of what society considers beautiful. Women strive to look just like the provocative women in these photographs. Similarily, to this day, women are still constantly comparing themselves to photogprahs of models. This has become more evident in shopping centers. When women shop at malls or clothing stores, or even beauty counters, they are constatnly faced with beauty selections for specifically youthful women. In both generations, it has been important for women to have a youthful face and to be skinny. For example, clothing stores are oriented for skinnier women because sizing is emphasized in shopping centers. In beauty counters, the ‘in-style’ look is to be youthful, to cover-up any flaws. Do these expectations for women to fit into these unrealistic standards of beauty correlate with the high statistic of women with eating disorders?
	Did you know that “approximatey 0.5 percent to 1 percent of young women will suffer from anorexia...?” (Kramer 2021). Anorexia is the lack of self-esteem, fear of gaining weight, and insufficent food intake. Anorexia emphasizes insecurities about the woman’s body figure. Anorexia can be correlated with the idea that girls and women need to be beautiful. Society’s idea of beautiful involves the expectation to be skinny. Individuals with anorexia may try to fit in by purging caloric intake and by avoiding proper nutrients just to fit in with society’s expecations. In concldusion, as Kramer discusses in her article, “the empahsis in American society on physical beauty, thinnness, dieting, and exercise plays a role in the prevlance of eating disorders...” (2021). 
	There are too many irrational expecations placed upon women. Women are not only facing inequality in social injustice, but also facing judgements based on physical appearance. Women suffer from eating disorders because of society’s standards of beauty. Just because women are politically more powerful than they were centuries ago, women are still struggling with mental illnesses and eating disorders. These illnesses are crucial because they can become fatal. The collective conscious of each society has an unjust, unfair, high standard for women to be beautiful in order to fit in with soicety. These societal pressures lead to these illnesses, so it is important to spread awareness about eating disorders before it becomes too late. Early intervention, such as therapy, is one of the best practices to prevent eating disorders from becoming suicidal or unhealthy. Not only does therapy prevent suicide, but it will also help build self-esteem and confidence in women. Moreoever, it is important to not ignore the constant pressure that women face politically, physically, and internally.

Society Shaping Slut-Shaming
Slaps on the back, fist pumps in the air, cheering, and hair ruffling. This is the exact reaction I have seen time and time again when a male walks in the room from a suggested sexual encounter. However, women lose girl friends, and make plenty of new guy friends, thanks to their new title as a “whore”. The morning after is comical for men, yet embarrassing, and creates feelings of guilt for women. Society celebrates men, but criticizes women, for the same sexual encounters because of the construct of gender roles, defined by the collective consciousness, and the role of anatomy in performing these roles.
Countless examples come to mind when considering this argument. I recently walked into a room with a guy, whom we will refer to as Kevin, from a late dinner on campus, but the image of us walking in together created a different idea. All of Kevin’s friends, particularly his roommate, were extremely excited. They exemplified the previously stated symptoms of celebration - the fist pumps and “ahhh I see you’s”. Watching this unfold, my face reddened from embarrassment, even though I knew that nothing had happened. 
Throughout the entire night, every time Kevin made his way to specifically talk to me, or touch me on the arm, or make any sort of “move”, cheers from the other men began. However, not a single girl spoke to me the rest of the night. I had officially won the unwanted title. I was made to feel guilty and outcast for something I did not even pursue. This is one of many, many similar experiences I have encountered in my relatively short lifespan.
Additionally, I have heard the gossip and the truth to many comparable experiences. Just a few nights ago, a girl, whom we will refer to as Carla, sent a photo of her and a guy to my dorm’s group chat. Only about half of their faces were visible, but because of the messiness of Carla’s hair, it was immediately assumed they “hooked up”. This girl had recently moved into our dorm, and only a few nights into meeting new people, she was automatically labeled a whore. Her ability to make her own positive impression disappeared. 
I was in the room with most of the people in the group chat, and the guys were shocked, impressed, yet also disgusted with her behavior. “Damn, he got with Carla?” was asked repeatedly. Her sexuality was discussed, and decided to be readily available and unwanted. Many of the women listening to the debate were just as disgusted as the men by her assumed actions, however, my roommate and I happen to be friends with Carla. My roommate reached out to her and told her what was being discussed. Carla was, understandably, extremely upset. She responded, explaining that she hadn’t even kissed the guy. Similar to my experience, Carla was made to feel guilty and outcast for something she had not even done.
While sex is assigned at birth, gender is a societal construction dictating how the male versus female should behave. Everyone is expected to “do gender” by conforming to their assigned, socially learned set of acceptable behaviors. This set of actions is created by the collective consciousness - a system in which the population creates a set of uniform ideals and standards based on overarching values, experiences, and practices. “Doing gender” is following these standards, and can be exemplified by women wearing longer hair and shorter shorts, while men do the opposite. Men “do gender” by acting tough and strong, while women submit to their dominance. Gender is an achieved status, in which one can become successful or fail, depending on the way each individual chooses to behave (West & Zimmerman). Our ability to perform these expected actions is specifically dictated by our physical bodies.
Each gender has been defined to have a specific body for a specific purpose. The male’s body is viewed as a direct and normal link to the world. However, for centuries, women have been seen as imprisoned, or held captive, by their bodies. Supposedly, women only think with their hormones, are held back by their ovaries and uterus, and are seen as incomplete. The woman is viewed only as a sexed being. The collective consciousness has defined a woman's purpose to make use of these hormones and internal organs and find a partner to complete them. Men, however, have been defined as perfectly complete by themselves, with the ability to think rationally and make decisions free of anatomical inhibition. Both men and women have hormones, yet our society has created the idea that women are completely dictated by these hormones, while men are completely unaffected (de Beauvoir).
This idea is also related to the toxic institution of hegemonic masculinity. This cultural practice legitimizes men’s dominance in society by celebrating the male gender role. Men are defined as strong, competitive, initiative-taking providers. The practice of these roles hurls men up the world’s socio-economic ladder, with new job opportunities and respected reputations. The beneficial outcome reestablishes the idea that men are the dominant, successful gender, and encourages men to continue being strong and independent (Stroudt).
Because the male is defined by strength and independence, sexual encounters are seen as an active choice. In other words, men can control their emotions and passions and reactivate these drives when they want to. They are celebrated for being strong, for leading the act with a level head, and for being independent. However, dictated by their hormones, women are viewed as “out of control” when acting on their emotions and participating in sexual behaviors. De Beauvoir’s exploration of the difference in purposes of the male and female body explains the expected actions and reactions of “the act”.
	Additionally, the idea that men supposedly control themselves, and consciously, actively engage in sexual activity reestablishes the idea that they are mentally, emotionally, and physically strong, and are dominant because of their self-control. This cycle furthers the institution of hegemonic masculinity, and thus furthers the idea that women need support and are too mentally weak to fight their emotions. The guilt and embarrassment women feel when accused of a sexual encounter stems from this idea. Women feel like they have done something wrong, that they should have been stronger, should have controlled themselves differently, should have presented themselves better, even when they did not participate in anything at all. 
	Men are celebrated, while women are criticized, for the exact same sexual actions, or even assumed sexual actions, in the exact same context. Sexual encounters reestablish men’s strength, independence, and dominance defined by their gender role. Becoming successful in this role grants men overall respect, and countless opportunities in the “real world”. This celebrated dominance instantly labels women as “the other” and treats half of the population as a weaker minority. 
As our society begins to shift to accept “girl-bosses” and female empowerment, it becomes even more embarrassing and frustrating for “slutty” actions to be assumed. Women desire to be respected, to be accepted for who they are, and to be viewed as controlled, intentional beings, who are more than just a sexed body. The assumptions that women are “too eager”, have “let their guard down”, have “lost control”, or just don’t have a desire for a sexual partner to “complete them”, invalidates the real emotions and intelligence hiding behind the hyperfocus on women’s hormones and uterus. In order to continue progression into a more equal and just world, we have to begin recognizing that men and women can both cultivate self-control, and both deserve respect, not punishment.

Inequalities in the Mental Health Care System 
	Mental health is extremely significant in American society as it constitutes part of an individual's identity. Although there is a consensus that mental health is very important, many groups in society have considerable barriers to accessing comprehensive health care. This begs the question: If mental health is so crucial to our society, why doesn’t everyone have equal access to it? According to Community of Hearts, an advocacy for the importance of mental health care, “1 in 4 people live with a mental health issue” (Community of Hearts). However, not all people who suffer with their mental health get appropriate care, especially minorities in America. This paper identifies how the mental health stigma, an individual's culture, and lack of resources discriminate in the mental health care system and create barriers to equitable access to proper care for minorities compared to non-Latino whites. 
In The Matrix of Domination, Patricia Hill Collins depicts how African American women have a perspective that should be utilized by society to advocate for change. By using an oppressed groups perspective, institutions are able to assess what needs to be changed to create a more inclusive mental health care system. The Matrix of Domination will be addressed throughout the paper to show that by focusing on oppressed groups, the American mental health care system can give minorities the accessibility and attention they deserve. 
	The stigma of mental health leads to a lack of people getting help for their mental illness because the stigma creates an illusion that it is something to be embarrassed about. Some people even feel like it is something you can’t talk about without negative repercussions.  Factors of these repercussions could be judgment from society, how they feel about getting help, and how their family and friends view mental health care. For example, an individual may be more hesitant to address their problems to a family member or friend on account of the backlash they might receive. The stigma can have extremely detrimental effects on an individual, as it prevents them from getting the help they need. A 2017 study by the APA proved, “greater self-stigma was associated with poorer recovery from mental illnesses after one and two years” (American Psychiatric Association). What this study by the APA indicates is that less people are getting the help they need as a result of the stigma associated with mental health harming your identity. Some effects of this harmful stigma can be strains on relationships, a negative self attitude, withdrawal from beloved activities, and so much more. Furthermore, the data shows that attributing a negative connotation to getting help for a mental illness is actively contributing to making the individual’s mental health worse. 
	Due to the negative connotation of receiving care for your mental health, groups in America fear the judgment of the public. These groups already receive judgment in the United States due to their race and culture, why would they want more? Throughout United States history, minorities in American have been segregated from non-Latino whites and stripped of respect. Fear is prevalent in their lives as they have to fight for equality every single day. Wiley Online Library states, “The fear of experiencing double discrimination- from mental illness and from being black- was a significant barrier to care” (Alang). The double discrimination expressed by Alang indicates how African Americans are scared that they will have one more thing to be discriminated against. The persistent discrimination against minorities in America for decades has instilled fear in them that the discrimination has the potential to get even more severe. 
	A lack of understanding for one’s culture has also constructed a barrier in certain groups in America from receiving proper mental health care. Cultures all have different rituals, narratives, and artifacts that form them, which are called collective representations. These factors can influence racial/ethnic groups not to seek help. According to Sage Journals, “Variation in cultural orientations, adherence to social norms, and location in the system may generate variation in self-labeling across racial/ethnic groups” (Villatoro). Villatoro describes in the Sage Journals article that certain groups will restrain from seeking help for a mental illness due to the beliefs their culture has instilled in them. For example, The American Psychiatric Association states, “in some Asian cultures, seeking professional help for mental illness may counter cultural beliefs of a strong family, emotional restraint, and avoiding shame” (American Psychiatric Association). The assertion made by The American Psychiatric Association illustrates that some Asian Americans are not willing to get help due to the collective representations their culture has embedded in them, such as it being shameful to seek help. Cultures around America differ in their beliefs and the way they carry themselves, which can influence their stance on whether they seek help for their mental health. 
	Alongside cultural barriers, If an individual cannot find someone proficient in their language for their mental health needs, it can create a barrier from receiving proper help as well. Language allows individuals and groups to communicate with one another in a plethora of ways; however, individuals speaking different languages can cause misunderstanding and affect the conversation immensely in a negative way. According to Psychiatry Online, “previous studies have shown that psychiatric patients with limited English proficiency underutilized specialist outpatient services and that those who did receive such services were less likely to participate in psychotherapy than fluent English speakers” (Alegria). The Psychiatry Online quote describes the difficulty those who do not speak English have in finding proper mental health care. Non-English speaking individuals have a hard time trying to navigate how to get help when they can’t engage in a conversation about their needs. 
	The lack of respect in American institutions towards minorities has caused oppressed groups to avoid seeking help from them, which reduces the resources available to them. According to the American Psychiatric Association, “only one-in-three African Americans who need mental health care receive it” (American Psychiatric Association). The policies, regulations and employment positions in American institutions have left oppressed groups feeling under-represented and unheard which alter their appeal to mental health care treatment. The Wiley Online Library conducted a study which showed an immense lack of trust in United States institutions from minorities. The study conveyed how “black people have gone into the mental health care system to get help, but have lost things that are important to them” (Alang). The conclusion made by the study shows how mistreatment in American systems has made oppressed people frightened to go back to them. In other words, the fear instilled in minorities due to oppression in American institutions is drastically reducing their urge to get the help they need. 
	Resources are a vital aspect to acquiring proper care for an individual’s mental health. The link discovered between race and availability to resources proved to stagger the opportunity of getting proficient help. Villatoro states,“the benefits of educational and economical resources for the identification of need for treatment and its response may not extend to racial/ethnic minority populations in the same way it benefits non-Latino whites” (Villatoro). Villatoro is concluding the benefits non-Latino whites have in accessing resources and being able to use them proficiently. Resources may conclude facilities and programs embedded in the community to connect people with information on how to seek help. The resources in your community allow easier access for help, but what if there is none? According to the Psychiatry Service article, “research has found that the more behavioral health specialists there are in a community, the more likely individuals are to use these services” (Alegria). The research states in the previous article that this is often seen with marginalized races or ethnicity, as well as within those experiencing poverty or homelessness. Non-Latino whites have an advantage over other races/ethnicity who do not commonly have the access to those crucial resources. 
	The sources throughout this essay conclude Collins' discussion in The Matrix of Domination on how oppressed people in our society have a beneficial perspective that should be looked at. When white men are the focus point of so many US institutions, the institutions are listening to the group that is the least oppressed in America. A black resident took note of this in the Wiley Online Library article by stating, “if the board of directors are all white, they should be asking themselves why” (Alang).  This retort suggests a reexamining of the people in charge of making the policies. When the least oppressed group is controlling the situations, it allows for unfair treatment towards minorities to be suggested. 
For Collins, African American women show a perspective that can illustrate where in the system inequalities are shown between minorities and non-Latino whites. By looking at this perspective, institutions can contribute to decreasing the stigma in communities. Decreasing stigma in communities can be attributed to evaluating where the stigma is stemming from and how the oppressed groups think it can be nurtured. The knowledge obtained from these groups when creating new policies and regulations in the mental health institutions is crucial for reducing the stigma in communities. 
Discussing an oppressed group's culture from their point of view allows a universal understanding of their needs. Not everyone will accept different cultures, but it is important to get members of mental health institutions to understand where their clients are coming from and how to help them to the best of their knowledge. The oppressed groups' knowledge is obtained from personal experience and is a direct correlation of how their culture has impacted them. Educating others on a culture has to come from an individual in that culture because those who are not oppressed cannot fully comprehend what it is like for them. 
Mental health care institutions can assess where they need more mental health care resources by attributing Collins theory. Primarily focusing on oppressed groups and services they lack, will lead to an increasing number of the population receiving proper mental health care. Collins summarizes the importance of community oppressed groups, such as African Americans, have sparked. Communities built by oppressed groups provide strength in fighting injustices. The communities need accessible resources for mental health that allow them to use their strength to help others and themselves. 
	 Learning from the current issues, such as the stigma, culture barriers, and lack of resources, we can ensure that the prominence of discrimination in our system can change for the better. Change can be attributed by placing those who are oppressed in the center of focus, so mental health institutions can identify factors that are wrong with the system. Mental health affects individuals everyday life and it is crucial to ensure proper care for it is taking place. In American society, individuals and systems need to influence change on expanding accessibility of mental health care resources. This change will not be an easy one; however, with reduction to the mental health stigma, cultural understanding, and proper allocation of resources, a definite improvement can be achieved in American society with equitable access for all.

The Role of the Collective Consciousness in Religious Discrepancies
Émile Durkheim, a renowned French sociologist, explored the societal dispositions caused by collective thought. By first defining collective representation as a symbol, artifact, or narrative that embodies collective belief, Durkheim had a reasonable explanation for the objective unification of a society. For example, America is united by the symbol of the American flag, and Christians are united by various Christmas traditions. Durkheim, however, still had to do some research into the effects of collective representation on the individual. 
Shortly afterwards, Durkheim discovered the related concept of collective consciousness. The collective consciousness is essentially the shared and intertwined sense of reality we all experience because of shared collective representations. Its purpose is to provide universal truths and values we can all understand, accept, and follow as individuals. Individuals collectively fabricated our society with the help of collective representations, thus creating a collective consciousness, in order to justify our own daily thoughts and actions. Traditions and objects were created and celebrated so that humans had a sense of meaning and a sense of unity. These traditions and objects, over generations, invented a collective mindset we all today share. For example, the tradition of gift-giving at Christmas time began as a way to pay respect to and honor the three kings that brought gifts to Jesus Christ. It gave citizens a sense of meaning and purpose, and brought the society together in humility and gratitude. After becoming a tradition, or norm, the act brought people together in likemindedness. The action of exchanging presents brought people together physically, and was then followed by a mental and emotional unification. The collective consciousness was formed thanks to collective representation. The mindset was created because of the accepted “object”.
Yuval Noah Harari, an Israeli historian and author, explored the related topic of the 2 versions of God. The first God is the “cosmic mystery”, the God that makes us ponder the purpose of life and the mysteries of the world. This God is the mystic aura that explains the deepest riddles of the universe. The first God is pretty much universally agreed upon and accepted. Many believe that there is some greater force, a greater being that knows all and watches over all. Though it may be vague, it is still an idea that universally connects our society.
The second God is the “worldly lawgiver”. This is the God that blurts out rules about dress, language, diet, appearance, sexual behavior, daily conduct, etc. This God is more controversial, more disagreed upon. In fact, this second God is what split up the Christian religion into dozens of denominations, creating rivalries and even hatreds of opposing groups. The first God is more of a general belief, while the second God creates daily rituals and practices. In reality, the two have no logical correlation. For example: why do the mysteries of the universe determine what length of dress a woman can wear? However, followers use various holy books that teach rituals and food taboos to justify the connection. 
Most people began with a general belief in a greater force, or higher being. But thanks to newly instituted (at least in the span of time) religious rituals, or collective representations, the mindset, or collective consciousness, has thus shifted. We, as humans, long to be a part of something bigger. We need a purpose, a higher reason, and we want to feel supported in it. We seek unity. Therefore, overtime, different groups have instituted different practices in order to coordinate our social lives. The shared goal to discover more about the “greater force” causes us to create shared plans, practices, etc. But obviously, sometimes people disagree. Different groups stuck together on different topics, and a variety of different religions were born. Even those basic religions broke off several more times to create different branches and denominations. As time goes on, more groups are created. Objects and habits, such as the Bible and its teachings, were created as physical structures to glue the institutions together. The Bible is an example of a collective representation. The variety of representations created, such as the Bible, the Tipitaka, the Quran and the Hadiths, and the Tanakh and the Talmud, paved the way for dozens of new mindsets, or collective consiousnesses, such as Christianity, Buddhism, Islam, and Judaism.
In other words, collective representation is to scripture as collective consciousness is to religion. The second God that Harari describes creates these divisions as new symbolic objects and belief systems integrate themselves into the world. The more divisions created in scripture and teachings, the more extreme the different collective consciousnesses become. The mindset of religion, defined as the first God, or collective consciousness, is formed thanks to collective representation, or the object of scripture or worship. The first God was originally a much broader topic, but as generations have instituted and accepted new collective representations, the first God has been redefined. There are now many new versions of this first God, based on any given specific belief system, which is why we now see so much rivalry and competition in religion rather than worship. In the effort to uncover truths and individual value systems, we have forgotten the basic, shared foundation in our first God. 
In order to recultivate our shared curiosity and love for the greater forces in the universe, and unify ourselves once again in vague belief, we must reevaluate the importance we place upon our various collective representations. Is it more important that we feel justified in our dress length and word usage, or that we are a unified society? At the very least, we should take just a few steps back, far enough where we can be civil, become educated about, and respect specific religions. Just as bloodshed is never the answer, convention will never bring peace. Rather than pushing practices onto people, we as a society should celebrate and worship the greater forces together and unite in the common goal for the betterment of society.

Hegemonic masculinity 
	While our culture has begun to place a greater emphasis on mental health issues, the impact mental health has on men is sometimes overlooked. The spread of McDonaldization in society
	Despite its name, the theory of McDonaldization actually spread in to a variety of other industries other than just fast food. Industries like banking, news papers, grocery shopping, schooling have all started to implement the ideals of McDonalization into their businesses. With each new generation we seem to be growing more and more impatient as a society with the expectation of instant satisfaction being at an all time high. The continuous evolution of the tech industry has become the biggest driving factor in all this as things like streaming services, online shopping, and social media continuing to fill our need for instant gratification. And in a world with 7 billion people and counting who expect all tasks to be performed with near perfect execution the theory of McDonalization has flourished. 
	Growing up there are very few sights that are more beloved than that of seeing two golden arches in the horizon while on a long road trip. Its the most gourmet meal you have ever had, the pinnacle of all restaurants, your yelling and pleading becomes more intense the closer you get, with the exit nearing you can almost taste those golden French fries, only to have your heart broken by your parents passing it by uttering the most heart breaking phrase “we have food at home”. While there were fast food restaurants before it and continue to be more after it McDonalds has truly perfected the formula when it comes to fast food.  The speed at which their food was made, the low price making it seemingly affordable for everyone, and the entertainment for the kids in happy meal toys and play grounds built into the establishment were all firsts with in the food industry. This was something that no restaurant before them had done before and catered perfectly to new ‘on the go’ family lifestyle that was beginning to be popularized. 
	However, as we continue to grow up there comes a time in all our lives where our tastes begin to change and allure of the golden arches starts to fade. For me this time was right before I started middle school, the happy meals no longer filled me up like they once did and I had started to get to big for the play place. It is at this point in life that we start to see the ideals from the McDonaldization theory being put in practice inside of the stores. There are four main ideals that the McDonaldization theory puts into practice, efficiency, calculability, predictability and standardization, and control. Efficiency is the choosing of means to reach and end rapidly and is usually portrayed as a benefit to the consumer but in reality is in the interests of the company. For example, drive thru windows and filling your own drink are both ways fast food restaurants cut costs as their employees are doing less work and making sure all the food is pre-made helps to speed up wait times letting the restaurants serve more customers faster. Calculability emphasizes the companies desire to have things like money and supplies calculated and accounted for as this lets companies know exactly how much each aspect of their product costs. Predictability and standardization refer to companies attempts to make sure that their products are all the same no matter where a consumer may buy them from. The best example of this comes from the fast food industry as you could go to any two McDonalds and a Big Mac would taste the exact same at both locations. The final ideal is control, which is what these companies want to have over their customers. Any company using the McDonaldization theory has a set way of doing things which is made abundantly clear to the customer as soon as the walk in the door. Take any fast food restaurant for example, it is expected of you to know what you want when you reach the register, money already out to pay, and then you stand off to the side while you wait. 
	The theory of McDonaldization was developed by sociologist George Ritzer in his book “McDonaldization of Society” which he released in 1993. Throughout this book, Ritzer is providing the reader with insightful knowledge about how the principles predominately found in the fast food industry are working their way into other aspects of society. Ritzer’s main basis for this argument comes from the theory of rationalization which was developed by Max Weber. In essence the theory of McDonaldization is the process of rationalization as one of its fundamental aspects is that any task should and can be rationalized. Rationalization is a sociology term that refers to the replacement of traditional decision motivators with the ideals of efficiency and rationality instead.  As a result of this the user is left with an easily controllable process of efficient and logical tasks that can be completed in the same manner each time to produce the same outcome without fail. 
	Outside of the obvious in McDonalds, on of the biggest corporations to adopt the McDonaldization theory is Amazon. With its continuous digital growth and focus on stream lined efficiency with their customers, Amazon has been able to use the McDonaldization method to create on of the most successful business to date. Its most basic principle being that of efficiency as Amazon has developed a straight forward direct to consumer sales approach that allows its customers to buy any product they need from their couch. There is also an aspect of predictability and calculability when shopping through Amazon because there are clear steps you need to follow when placing your order and when you do you know exactly how much it is all going to cost as the prices of products are clearly marked on the website. 
	Another major industry that has seen more of a reliance on the McDonaldization method is banking. Going to the bank used to be an ordeal that could last you hours but now with the advancements in technology the whole process has become for more efficient and calculated. Some of the biggest ways that the banking industry has become more efficient is through ATMs, mobile deposits, direct deposits, and the ability to automatically pay your bills. The efficiency in banking has grown drastically through the use of ATMs allowing use to withdraw money at any given time and the development of mobile deposits which allows us to cash checks with just a few photos. Auto bill pay has also helped with efficiency as customers can now have their bills automatically paid straight out of their account each month instead of having to deal with paying bills manually. Calculability has also seen a sharp increase now that we banks have developed their own apps, allowing us to see exactly how much money is in our accounts at all times. 
	The media has also been affected by the McDonaldization theory as news outlets are producing more stories that, like the food found at McDonalds, are fast easy reads that lack any true substance for the consumer. Many of the stories now are written with the hopes of reaching as wide of an audience as possible and usually are very cheap to produce maximizing profits. The biggest form of media that utilizes the McDonaldization method is social media. Social media has a focus on quick content that are meant to keep the audiences attention for long periods of time. Prime examples of this are the apps Tik Tok and Instagram as they produce short meaningless clips that use the simple act of swiping to keep the audience engaged. 
	Overall the McDonaldization theory has seen continued success in a variety of different industries over the years with many more industries starting to adopt its ideals. Its focus on the four main ideals of efficiency, calculability, predictability, and control make it easy for any company to adopt and helps to satisfy our ever growing need for instant satisfaction as a society. As our society continues to grow and as technology continues to advance, the theory of McDonaldization will grow as well finding its way into even more industries in the future.

Racism and Prejudice in Contemporary Society
	Why do individuals of color face racism and prejudice from all angles of society? Judgment based upon race and ethnicity is omnipresent within contemporary society and extends much farther than the traditional discussion. Often, when discussing the plight of individuals of color, it can seem that these individuals are solely oppressed by the dominant social group. This dominant social group is said to be well-to-do white individuals, who are primarily male. However, people of color face judgment and prejudice from not only the dominant social group but also those in their own social group and those of similar ethnicities. Individuals of color and of various ethnicities face this racialization from other minorities as well as the individuals within their own race or social class. Why is it that minorities face this hardship from not only the dominant group but also other minorities? It is a complex issue that has a complex reasoning behind it. While it may be easy to assume that individuals of the same race or similar minority status would have a shared empathy for one another, this is often not the exact reality. 
	The roots of this issue are based on the fact that there is a ‘matrix’ nature to social status and privilege. This matrix is known as the ‘Matrix of Domination’ which explains the varying levels of privilege in society by acknowledging how the characteristics of race, ethnicity, gender, and sexuality all intersect. This matrix gives way for varying levels of privilege and can often pose minority groups against one another, creating prejudice and racialization from all sides. This phenomenon can be observed in various situations within the lives of individuals in contemporary society.
	Throughout my own childhood, I have seen the levels of privilege and reracialization amongst minorities take form in many situations. This has primarily been observed through my involvement in the sport of soccer. I have played soccer throughout my entire life, beginning when I was around 5 years old. I have continued on to play soccer in middle school, high school, and still today while in college. Along the way, I have made many Hispanic friends who are deeply engaged in the culture of the sport. Due to our similar passions, I have built a strong connection with the Hispanic community throughout my childhood. Many of my current friends are Hispanic and frequently invite me to cultural gatherings and family events. I even currently play on an adult league soccer team that is exclusively Hispanic aside from myself. This team, made up of many of my best friends, plays and practices together every week and often go out for dinner together. 
	One of my many experiences with this team came several months ago when we had an open practice that anyone could attend. As usual I arrived early with one of my best friends, Adrian, and a few others on the team. When we arrived at the park, the field we normally practice on was taken up by a large group playing flag football. The rest of the team and I all waited by our cars as more and more people showed up for our upcoming practice. As the time for practice arrived, the field was still occupied and everyone on my team started to get a bit frustrated. As we all stood around, some of the Hispanic players began to talk to each other about the people taking up the field in a very crude way. These people playing football were primarily black and the Hispanic individuals started using racial slurs amongst each other and making many racist comments. I was shocked that they were so disgusted and offended by these black individuals doing absolutely nothing wrong. Eventually, we were able to practice and these comments eventually stopped. However, this was not the last time I saw this happen. 
	Not only did I see this type of racial judgment and prejudice applied to individuals of another race, I also saw Hispanics do this within their own ethnicity. Many of the hispanics who come to practice are Mexican or Honduran, while some come from other backgrounds. During one game in particular, we played against a primarily Columbian team who were made up of individuals of a different heritage and slightly different complexion. After the game, several slurs were used between players of my team and the Columbians. Both seemed to be very resentful of each other and judge each other based on their complexion and heritage.
Patricia Collins explains this phenomenon in relation to the concept of the “matrix of domination”. The matrix of domination is made up of various levels and determines an individual's privilege based on their race, gender, sexuality, etc. In this matrix, each individual has a position determining their privilege. Collins states the following, “Depending on the context, an individual may be an oppressor, member of an oppressed group, or simultaneously oppressor and oppressed” (Collins 405). The dominant group made up of white, well educated, male individuals are positioned at the top while subordinate groups fall beneath. Amongst these subordinate groups, there are differences in heritage, education, race, etc that determine their level of privilege in relation to the matrix. All social aspects of an individual intersect to determine a person's “position” in this hierarchy of perceived status.
In relation to my personal experiences, the Hispanic individuals on my team have a position on the matrix of domination. Being that they are Hispanic, they are often oppressed by the dominant group on both a systemic and personal level. Not only are they oppressed due to their race but also their ethnic background. However, they see themselves as positioned higher on this matrix than black individuals. It is almost as if subordinate groups seek to position themselves closer to the dominant group and distinguish themselves from other subordinate groups. In an effort to position themselves as not completely subordinate, the Hispanic individuals in my personal example choose to oppress another minority group. Thus, Blacks face prejudice from not only the dominant group but also other minorities who seek to impose the same oppression as the dominant group in an effort to advance their social position. There is almost a mindset amongst the Hispanic community that while they are oppressed, they are not at the lowest position on the matrix of domination.
Not only does oppression occur across different minority groups, it can also occur within a particular minority or amongst a certain ethnic group. This concept is discussed in Tomas Almaguer’s piece, “Race, Racialization, and Latino Populations in the United States”. Almaguer states, “these groups [Mexicans and Puerto Ricans] then reracialize each other under the discursive logic that structures the meaning of race in the United States' ' (63). This means that minority groups apply similar patterns of racism as the dominant groups amongst their own ethnicity/race. This reracialization occurs as race is a symbolic concept and there is an established logic of a racial hierarchy which individuals seek to perpetuate. Not only is racism applied from the dominant group but also across the individuals of a particular subordinate group.
The Mexican individuals of my soccer team exemplify this instance of reracialization amongst the Latino community. The Columbians and Mexicans that I met, have similar cultural backgrounds and experiences of oppression. However, the Mexican individuals attempt to position themselves higher on the ‘racial hierarchy’. To do so, these individuals apply the same patterns of racism as the dominant group does. In turn, a structure of hierarchy is created amongst their own ethnicity. Through applying racism amongst their own ethnicity, these individuals seek to position themselves as a dominant group within their own Latino community. The negative ideas of blackness that are present within the United States are imposed amongst individuals within the Hispanic community as well, explaining why these Mexican individuals have a negative outlook on the ‘darker skinned’ Columbians on the opposing team. The same structures of racism that oppress the Hispanic community are utilized by Hispanics to oppress other Hispanic individuals and establish a separate social hierarchy where one group is dominant to the other. 
The plight of individuals of color is complex as there is not only systemic racism that they face but also a reracialization by other individuals of color. Each individual in contemporary society seeks to improve or maintain a particular status. No one wants to be considered to be at the very bottom of the matrix of domination. Thus, oppressed individuals seek to oppress others in an effort of self advancement and placement in a higher social status. The logic of a racial hierarchy is not only perpetuated by the individuals with the most privilege, but also those who are oppressed. This makes for an experience of racism and prejudice that is very complex for individuals of color in contemporary society.

	Sixty years ago, most would question a man who darkened his skin.  Surprisingly, skin-darkening is essential to 21st-century white Americans.  To such claim, one may argue that “white people aren’t dark-skinned, so what have they done?”.  Counterarguments are ironically self-damaging, for skin alteration is so commonplace that it camouflages itself as beauty. Truly, black people’s culture is interpreted by many as “cool”, though black people’s struggles are undesired.  As non-black Americans want not to be black, but rather black-adjacent, corporate America monetizes olive skin.  Using James Cooley’s concept of the “looking-glass self”, Americans of all races internalize society’s “light-skin” obsession, which we measure our value with.  
Romil Hemnani, producer for rap group Brockhampton, once said, “I want to live in the White House”.  Here, Hemnani is not referring to the office of the President, but rather to a figurative structure that exclusively benefits white people.  For clarity, Hemnani is a brown-skinned Pakistani man.  In expressing his reservations for those who are racially privileged, Hemnani conveys a belief that is shared by millions of American minorities: fair skin makes life easier.  Needless to say, slavery’s horrors are not still existent, and the days of pre-1964 are behind us.  Yet, public schools remain largely segregated, incarceration is racially disproportionate, and low wages primarily affect minority workers.  America’s racist policy is blatant. Lip fillers, butt lifts, braids, and other Afrocentric features are occasionally assumed by non-black women.  A general population of non-black Americans don articles of clothing that are associated with hip-hop culture.  Attempts, by non-black people, to present themselves as black are ever-present in both suburbia and high-profile circles; celebrities like Madonna, Kylie Jenner, and Kim Kardashian-West have publicly presented themselves as black-adjacent. 	For many non-black Americans, particularly those who are neither non-black nor a separate minority, privilege is one hell of a drug. Meanwhile, many dark-skinned people undergo surgeries to disassociate themselves from others who look similar.  In both cases, Americans want to appear “light-skinned”, which implies a black complexion that is light when compared to dark-skinned black complexions.  American beauty standards are so olive-toned that they are expected, but other countries encourage Eurocentric standards of beauty.  American magazines are significantly “white”, but general media tells a different story, one that includes racial ambiguity.  American society’s obsession with a light-skinned aesthetic may be explained by Charles Cooley’s “looking-glass self”.  Cooley was an American sociologist who developed numerous theories of societal effects on one’s self, but the “looking-glass self” remains his most famous concept.  The “looking-glass self” refers to a self-perception that is based on how one is perceived by others.  This concept is dependent on how one’s self appears in another’s mind, similar to psychologist William James’ “social self”.  According to Cooley, we decide our peers’ opinions regarding us, and we base our self-confidence, self-worth, and self-value on these imaginations.  Subsequently, we either dislike ourselves or like ourselves.  With relation to society’s focus on racial ambiguity, the “looking-glass self” places value on olive skin.  This particular “looking-glass self” is accredited to several factors, and efforts of non-black people’s to be associated with blackness are proof.

That said, individuals cannot alter systems in a similar manner that is used to alter town-wide trends.  Social media has supplied youth with additional influence on fashions, styles, and trends.  Youth’s proximity to aesthetics is much, much closer than their proximity to anti-black institutions, and the former is how a light-skinned ideal has fogged millions of non-black minds.  Simultaneously, visually multiracial beauty standards communicate value, which defines the “looking-glass self” at hand.  In most cases, the “looking-glass self” is regarded as a basis for one’s satisfaction with himself/herself that is, in-and-of itself, based on other’s opinions of him/her.  The “looking-glass self” is a concept comparable to American psychologist George Mead’s “social self”, which assumes we internalize other’s opinions.  The social self is popular as a sociological concept, and it concedes that our identities are conceived using socialization.  The “looking-glass self” is, essentially, cousins with Mead’s “social self” because it advocates that an individual’s self-value is correlated with widely-held beliefs regarding him/her.  
	Described by the “looking-glass self” is a cognitive process that utilizes perception to interpret social contexts.  That said, social ability is vital to one’s understanding of the world.  In 2021, for example, users of Instagram recognize a relationship between popularity and monetary value.  Influencers may gain popularity by posting photos that alter their skin tones to match those of mixed-race people. Who defines gender? We, as a society, have a subconscious set of guidelines for the expression of gender and how individuals that identify with a specific gender should portray themselves, but who is coming up with these concepts and social expectations of gender expression? The definition and social construct of gender is constantly changing and being redefine in society. However, society knows these guidelines we subconsciously have for gender, but how do we formulate those common expectations? 
	Throughout much of history, women were seen as the inferior gender. Women were considered to be weak, frail, emotional, and their purpose was to take care of the house, children, and serve their husband. Women were seen as needy, and they were expected to get married and rely on their husband to provide them with basic needs. However, men were thought of as the providers or supporters of the family. It was the man’s duty to work, put food on the table, and put a roof over their family’s head. Men were considered to be tough, emotionless, and superior. Men were the head of the household, the ones making all of the decisions for the family as a whole. These ideas within the gender roles have begun to change over the past few decades as individuals begin to challenge these roles and standards. Women are becoming more independent of men, obtaining a higher level of education, working towards equality in the job market, both genders making money along with providing for the family, sharing responsibilities at home, and more. However, if we see an individual walking past us on the sidewalk, wearing a skirt, floral blouse, has very short hair, has facial hair, is wearing tennis shoes, and is carrying a bookbag, we will be a little confused and not sure quite what their gender is exactly, just based on the characteristics they are expressing, since they are not completely consistent with a specific gender as determined by societal norms.

We define gender based on how the collective consciousness of society views gender. The collective consciousness is constantly changing as the values, beliefs, norms, and ideas of a society change. We can see this very prominently in today’s society as the fight to change gender expression and gender norms is ongoing, especially in the younger generation.

The collective consciousness of a society has the biggest impact on how society collectively views gender and what the accepted norms are for gender and expression. This concise representation of the ideas behind gender are constantly changing and being rewritten. The collective consciousness is constantly being challenged in a way that gender is becoming more and more fluid. The Paradox of Heather
I wish I were Heather. In the beginning of 2020, I heard this lyric countless times. I would scroll for hours on end on TikTok, watching girls compare themselves to celebrities, influencers, models – any woman who they believed to be perfect; any woman they deemed a Heather. This was a trend that had taken off on TikTok rather quickly. Given that this was the beginning of quarantine, teenagers spent much of their time online to make up for the lack of social interaction. In doing so, women began to closely follow the lives of beautiful and famous models and celebrities, which bred comparison. Young girls found comfort in each other, creating an environment where they could speak freely about their insecurities and self-image issues with no fear of judgement. This trend allowed women to display their despair about feeling inferior to other woman, feeling as though they weren’t, and could never be as beautiful, as skinny, as tan, as popular as these women; that I could never be Heather. 
After watching so many of these videos, I began to feel the same way: How could anyone ever think I’m beautiful, when there are women who look like that?! Although there were many different women who were deemed Heathers, all of them had an indescribable quality. Everything about them was beautiful – and everything they had was something I felt I lacked in myself. When looking at these girls, I couldn’t help but envy them. The beauty standard for women is regarded as completely unattainable, but somehow, they were able to perfectly embody it. 
Not only were these women beautiful, but they were popular, rich, and famous – more things I could never be. Although I knew some of them spent thousands of dollars on plastic surgery and continued to pay for injections, that didn’t affect how I felt. I still wanted to be them. I still wanted to be free from insecurity and the thought that I could never be worthy of anything.  
I continued to watch the videos, and after some time, I noticed something. The women who originally posted these videos were Heathers. They were the women that others were scrupulously comparing themselves to. As I continued to watch these videos and notice this pattern, I began to feel differently. Being Heather wouldn’t keep me from feeling insecure or stop me from comparing myself to other women. Women that I felt were the beauty standard still felt the same insecurity that I did, and still found women who they deemed to be perfect. 
In reading comments, I found that many other women had reached the same conclusion. So many girls felt that they were so below what was considered perfect, when others found them to surpass that. Naomi Wolf explains the reason why women think this way about themselves. Wolf describes women being judged based off their appearance as the beauty myth. The beauty myth is defined as, “An obsession with physical perfection that traps the modern woman in an endless spiral of hope, self-consciousness and self-hatred as she tries to fulfill society’s impossible definition of the flawless beauty.” This concept is a violent backlash against feminism because it uses images of female beauty as a political weapon against women’s advancement. Wolf argued that the beauty myth affected women in multiple categories such as work, religion, sex, violence, and hunger. This myth established by the mind of men has carried its way into the mind of women immensely which has caused a mass amount of competition between women. Due to the competition women face with one another, because of a man’s idea of a perfect woman, has prohibited the ability for women to create a community. Men have been able to hold onto their power over women because of this. Women must learn and start to oppose of the beauty myth and see their worth through more than just their looks. 
Every woman wants to be Heather because that’s what men have deemed as perfect. The unrealistic beauty standard that women try to achieve doesn’t necessarily reflect their own personal beliefs, rather, the ideal woman that men have defined.  While men are not the ones who are the targets of the standard of beauty for women, they still are the primary influence for what it is.
Why do women stare at celebrities every day idolizing their looks? Why do women constantly compare themselves to unrealistic standards of beauty? Why do I want to be anyone but myself? The beauty myth, created by the minds of men, has taken over the way women perceive their worth. The beauty myth has convinced a lot of women that they need to be flawless or else they aren’t worthy of love, or respect. 
Many women have begun to believe that when they get cheated on, it’s because they weren’t pretty enough, or they just weren’t enough in general for their boyfriend at the time. This was a sentiment I shared. I believed that I got cheated on because I wasn’t pretty enough for him. But now, I realize I can’t blame myself or my looks for the wrongdoing of a man. I recognized that I blamed my looks because the beauty myth created by men was engraved into my mind regarding my self-worth. The beauty myth explains why I’m sometimes unaware of what I deserve because I’m so wrapped around the idea that I wasn’t perfect enough for him; that he cheated on me because the other girl was much prettier, and I should’ve done better. 
The beauty myth has rerouted the minds of women into thinking that they are the problem. That they weren’t pretty enough for their boyfriend to remain loyal to them. Wolf states, “It is no accident that so many potentially powerful women feel this way.” The beauty myth impacts so much of a women’s own worth and respect. Women need to come together to take down the power men hold over their self-worth. They need to break the unrealistic cycle of beauty created by men that has gone on for countless years. 
Women put so much pressure on themselves to seek out perfection due to the beauty standard created by men in society. I see this everywhere on social media and specifically through “the Heather” trend on TikTok. Beautiful women and girls comparing themselves to other beautiful women. Beautiful women blaming themselves for the disloyalty of a man. Beautiful women suppressing their worth because of their looks. The beauty myth has disrupted the raw understanding of the world, that everyone deserves the best in life no matter who you are or what you look like. Women must come together to fight the unrealistic standards created by men and men must stop putting so much pressure on women to fit such unrealistic standards of beauty. Women must learn to believe that they are deserving of everything and anything no matter their looks. There shouldn’t continue to be a beauty standard through the eyes of men, there should be a beauty standard created by a woman for that woman and no one else. Every woman is Heather, and every woman should fight to break the unrealistic beauty standard and take their power back.

How Gender Affects the Workforce

Our personal beliefs and morals are heavily influenced by society and the people in it. As a society, we have determined that gender is dichotomous and an important social identity. This means our conception of gender is part of our collective consciousness. The collective consciousness is the shared beliefs and values that connect individuals in a society. In other words, we view society through a group consciousness. In his article “The Cultural Logic of Collective Representations,” Emile Durkheim explains this phenomenon in terms of religion. He writes, “Thus the collective ideal which religion expresses is far from being due to a vague innate power of the individual, but it is rather at the school of collective life that the individual has learned to idealize.”  In this quote, Durkheim explains that our values do not stem from individuals, but that individuals learn to idealize certain values. According to Durkheim, these shared ideas are manifested through collective representations in the form of rituals, artifacts, symbols, and values. This is true for gender, as it is represented in art, advertisements, language, celebrations, institutions, etc. The idea of two distinct genders is a common belief that is deeply rooted in our society. The gender binary stems from the concept of sex. This comparison is inaccurate, however, as there are some key differences. According to authors Candace West and Don H. Zimmerman in “Doing Gender,” sex is determined by biology, anatomy, and hormones. Gender, in contrast, is achieved through psychology, culture, and social means. The two are connected through a concept known as sex category, or the identifying features that categorize someone as male or female. West and Zimmerman argue that because of this, gender is something we “do” when we align our outward appearance and behavior with those expected of a specific sex category. For this reason, western society believes that men and women are inherently different, with phycological and behavioral discrepancies that can be determined based on reproductive organs. This aspect of our collective consciousness has been used to justify the social consequences of assuming “gender roles.”
Throughout history, the female gender has been considered inferior. In the article “Women as Other,” author Simone de Beauvoir argues this is because women have always been considered the “other” in society while men are considered absolute. Beauvoir argues that this ideology didn’t just appear, as women have always been treated as subordinates. Women often submit to this point of view because they do not have a history, religion, or community of their own separate from men. Women have always been tied to men, and therefore have been unable to separate from their oppressors. This historical mistreatment of women is evident when examining the unequal division of labor in western society. In the article “Two worlds of female labour: gender wage inequality in western Europe 1300-1800,” authors Alexandra de Pleijt and Jan Luiten Van Zanden examine the underutilization of women in European labor markets from 1300-1800. Pleijt and Zanden argue that for women to be autonomous and remain single, they must be able to earn a living wage. Additionally, women participating in labor increased the human capital formation, but required women to be educated, skilled, or limit their fertility, all of which were undesirable for the time. For this reason, opportunities for women to work were not comparable to that of men. Following the Black Death, poor economies and low population required more women to join the workforce. In southern Europe, the gender wage ratio was approximately 0.5. In northern Europe, however, the gender wage ratio was much higher at 0.8. In medieval England, there were legal constraints that discouraged young, single women from working casually, and many were not allowed to work enough days to earn a livable wage. The sixteenth century market a time of labor market slack, in which the demand for labor was less than supply. This resulted in the gender wage ratio decreasing rapidly, with women making less than half of that of men. This trend continued through the nineteenth century. By examining these statistics, it becomes clear that gender has played a key role in determining who can participate in the labor market. This was a strategic decision to prevent women from making a living wage and becoming independent from men.
Because women were often unable to make a living wage, they were forced to marry young. A consequence of this is that women were often unskilled and uneducated. This allowed the traditional gender roles to remain intact as women became reliant on their husbands. Women were valued in society only for their fertility and were often patronized by their husbands. An example of this can be seen in Charlotte Gilman’s “The Yellow Wallpaper.” In this story, the main character’s husband, who is a physician, refuses to believe she is sick and insists that she is just hysterical. For this reason, she spends many hours in her room, unable to write or work. The woman feels guilty for not feeling more grateful for her husband, but she cannot deny her feelings of resentment. She directs this resentment towards her yellow wallpaper, a metaphor for the oppression she experiences as a woman. This demonstrates the struggle many women faced in the ninetieth and twentieth centuries. During this time, many women were unable to work or pursue an education. This often left women at the mercy of their husbands, who considered them hysterical for expressing resentment towards their gender roles. This power dynamic can also be seen in the cult of domesticity.
Throughout history, women have been denied career opportunities and burdened with domestic duties such as childbearing, cooking, and cleaning. This reflects the cult of domesticity, or the belief that women should embrace these duties and create a loving home. As a result, women complete approximately 2/3 of all domestic work. Women are primarily responsible for the tasks that must be completed daily, while men complete scheduled maintenance. Domestic responsibilities are time consuming, especially raising children. This can prevent women from pursuing careers and fulltime jobs, often leaving them unemployed or employed part time. Women who work fulltime are not exempt from these duties, however, as many are involved in a junior partner/senior partner relationship. These relationships exist when both partners have careers, but the woman has a “second shift“ in which she must also complete domestic work. This issue has only worsened recently due to the covid-19 pandemic. In the article titled “A gendered pandemic: Childcare, homeschooling, and parents’ employment during COVID-19,” authors Richard Pettes, Daniel Carlson, and Joanna Pepin explain that the availability of domestic support like daycare and school are important for mother’s labor force participation, while father’s participation is generally unaffected. As a result of daycares and schools closing due to covid and the domestic labor that follows, mother have been significantly more likely to reduce their work hours. According to Petts, Carlson, and Pepin as of April 2020, the beginning of lockdowns, the unemployment rate for women was 16.2% and 13.5% for men. This is an example of traditional gender roles in which women are responsible for childcare and housework and men for breadwinning. The responsibilities associated with each gender are harmful to women, as they are often unable to participate in the workforce due to responsibilities at home.
Though women have made many advancements in the workforce, there are still many obstacles. One example is the gender pay gap. In the article “The Gender Wage Gap: Extent, Trends, and Explanations,” authors Francine Blau and Lawrence Kahn examine why and how the pay gap has changed. According to Blau and Kahn, there are several reasons why the pay gap exists. Firstly, familial attitudes and gender norms often reduce women’s work life and discourage them from pursuing formal schooling. Secondly, women tend to gravitate towards lower paying college majors like art as opposed to science. Thirdly, it is often difficult for women to make advancements in the workplace due to bias. In the early twentieth century, women made approximately 60% as much as their male counterparts. Around 1980, however, women’s wages rose, and the gap changed to around 67%. This trend has continued at around 79% today. Blau and Kahn argue that this improvement is due to the shrinking education and experience gaps. In 1981 only 15.3% of women had a bachelor's degree and 13.5 years of work experience, with men at 18.1% and 20.3 years. These gaps have shrunken, with 24.7% of women in 2011 having a bachelor’s degree and 16.4 years of experience, with men at 26.2% and 17.8 years. The gender wage gap reveals that women often receive less opportunity for advancement and higher paying jobs based solely on the concept of gender. These statistics show the division of labor between genders.
Gender is a social construct embedded in our collective consciousness. As a society, we have come to believe that there are two inherently different genders who assume different roles. This idea is ingrained in our institutions and affects many aspects of our society. This is extremely evident when examining the workforce. Throughout history, it has been difficult for women to find and maintain job opportunities because of traditional ideas of gender, as women are mostly responsible for domestic labor. This made women reliant on their husbands and has kept them as the “other” in society. Though women have made advancements, the gender wage gap and the unequal unemployment caused by the covid-19 pandemic are continuous reminders that there is still progress to be made. By adjusting our understanding of gender, we can create equal opportunities for everyone in society.
