Patricia Collins advocates that the known studies of systematic disadvantage have been biased, only one race has studied the effects of racism on communities. Because of this biased research, she believes that scientists should approach the study in a different manner. She believes that the first step to freedom and rights for every group, even those considered minorities, begins with acknowledging intersectionality, the combination of different race and ethnic groups, including the different genders. Once awareness of different personal, cultural, and institutional knowledge is spread, scientists will be able to gain a better understanding of inequality. The Podcast “Get Back to Where You Once Belonged” is a prime example of spreading awareness.
	“Get Back to Where You Once Belonged” was an interview with a woman of African descent. She talks about the struggles she faced as an African American, light skinned, woman. She illustrates the feelings of unease, the feeling of being out of place. At a young age, Lily was faced with unfair stereotypes and cruel comments. Unknowingly, she would defend the perpetrators with the defense that these kids were just ‘ignorant’. She held high spirits, she chose to see the good in the people causing social unjust. Lily lived in Russia with her family because, although Russia wasn’t considered Utopia for racism, Russia stood by the fact that they were less racist than the United States during World War II. African Americans stood by the Soviet Union in hopes for a better, more free life. Lily’s family took the option to move to Russia, but still faced hardships, and although Lily chose to have good faith in her society, she was still oppressed. She talked about her damaged self-esteem, the feeling of loneliness, and the lack of trust in her community. Lily tried to date a Russian boy, but instead, she was faced with a cruel racist nickname, she even believed that the Russian boy was only dating her to see what it was like to date a black woman. She became more self-conscious of her skin as she grew older, but she also grew wiser. She talks about her philosophical beliefs about facing racism as a woman of color. She believes that in order to live a satisfying life of a minority, it is important to stop listening to the voice in her head blaming every little wrong on the color of her skin. She believes that she, and people like her, should just live their life, they should stop wasting time trying to change to conform to society and instead, drop the racist people who segregate, and continue to live life with people who aren’t threatening. She ended up living a satisfying life as she grew older, she learned how to adjust to the oppression in order to be happy. 
	“Get Back to Where You Once Belonged” is an important illustration of racialization. Racialization is the process that became ethnic identity, it’s the process of counting and defining immigrants because they went against the norms of society -- the norms that the collective consciousness created. As society grew and advanced, the creation of community formed. Ethnic identities were based on commonalities. Lily, from “Get Back to Where You Once Belonged” faced racialization living in a community unlike the people of her own culture. She felt lonesome due to lack of commonalities with her community, she felt out of place because her identity was outnumbered by people of different identities. Lily had to adapt to a social hierarchy, as discussed by Collins in “Black Feminist Thought in the Matrix of Domination” that went against her ethnic identity. It’s important to spread awareness, to acknowledge institutionalized differences in order to create liberation for every community, including minorities. The influence of social media and “fake news” on the spread of ideas across society 
Mollie Clary 
University of North Carolina Wilmington

















	The rapid development of technology has changed the way we live in countless ways. One way is the increase in the spread of ideas and connectivity of the world through social media. According to Statista, in 2020, social media users included over 3.6 billion people worldwide. An implication of the prevalence of social media is the significant amount of false information that is spread throughout the population and perceived as truth by thousands, if not millions of people. In the United States, this issue came to light during the 2016 presidential election when Donald Trump utilized the phrase “fake news!” throughout his campaign and presidency. “Fake news,” or false information disguised as truth, can be difficult to distinguish from credible news information. Additionally, an increasing number of people are turning to social media as an avenue for consuming news, where anyone has the freedom to post whatever they want. This is why it is so important to recognize and identify this dangerous force as it relates to the spread of ideas, beliefs, and the development of a collective consciousness. 
	Durkheim argued for the existence of collective belief and idea systems throughout society. He believed that religion contributed to this collective consciousness which can be observed through collective representations. Collective representations are symbols that exist in society and have meanings placed upon them that have become fabricated and prevalent through the development of society. The concept of the collective consciousness is important to acknowledge because it can explain a lot about our society and can help us understand why certain behaviors and ideas are popular among the general population and among certain groups. In our current American society, there are various groups that have strong belief systems that are consistent among members of the group. For example, the groups of this kind that get the most attention are Democrats and Republicans. The belief systems of these groups have become more and more solidified and polarized through the use of social media. Fake news is important to fit into this narrative because it can help explain some of the tension between these two groups in the United States. 
	A study conducted in 2018 by Pennycook and colleagues sought to examine the relationship between exposure to fake news headlines and perceived accuracy of these headlines. There is a previously proven idea in psychology called the “illusory truth effect” which is the process of being exposed to information and therefore being more likely to perceive the information as accurate, solely based on the fact that one was exposed to it, sometimes even only subconsciously exposed. This theory says that there is a positive relationship between amount of exposure to information and perceived accuracy of the information. Pennycook and colleagues (2018) attempted to understand whether or not the illusory truth effect would apply to fake news headlines that seem less plausible than the information used in previous research that examined this effect. In order to do this, they conducted three studies with slightly different conditions. The first study included “trivia” statements that were easily identifiable as highly implausible. Researchers concluded that exposure/repetition to these statements had no impact on perceived accuracy due to the high implausibility of the statements. 
The second study conducted by Pennycook and colleagues in 2018 included fake news headlines which included warnings about the possible inaccuracy of the information being presented. The results of the second study indicated that exposure to these headlines, (whether true or false, regardless of whether there was a warning indicating possible false information, and regardless of whether the information agreed with the person’s political identity) increased perceived accuracy of the information. The third study found that exposure positively influences perceived accuracy of information, even with a week-long delay. Researchers pointed out that these findings have significant implications related to everyday life. For example, when politicians repeatedly communicate an idea to the public, based on these findings, people will be more likely to accept it; and the same applies to other ideas that may be impossible to definitively confirm or deny, such as religious beliefs (Pennycook et al., 2018). This study reinforces the idea that a high amount of exposure to information through social media, regardless of whether it is true, has a significant impact on the evolution of our collective consciousness and belief systems. 
	The social aspect of this issue is highly important to acknowledge because our belief systems are highly influenced by our environment. “Groupthink” is a phenomenon in psychology that occurs as a cycle, when group members’ beliefs are strengthened through the influence of the group (Groupthink, n.d.). Individuals in society often classify themselves and are perceived to be included in many groups whether these groups are imaginary or institutional. According to Psychology Today, Groupthink is similar to the concept of conformity, but exclusively occurs during decision-making processes related to a group. The Psychology Today article explains that Groupthink can have dangerous implications when it occurs in parts of society that contain large scale groups such as politics. This is because the phenomenon of Groupthink can cause people to dismiss ethics and morals in favor of conforming to their group’s priorities. According to Psychology Today, “(“an ‘us versus them’ mentality”)… can prompt members to accept group perspectives, even when those perspectives don’t necessarily align with their personal views.” This displays the high impact of Groupthink on individuals. This phenomenon is important to note in the context of fake news and its impact on societal beliefs because it definitely seems to play a role in the perceived accuracy of fake news. For example, when Donald Trump and some media outlets downplayed the Coronavirus pandemic, it appears that many Republicans went along with these ideas. This was very dangerous because it prompted many people to disregard important CDC community safety guidelines; some even protesting important aspects of these guidelines such as mask-wearing. The simple use of the phrase “fake news” adds to a general mistrust of the media which could lead to issues for our society. 
	Research conducted by Colliander in 2019 examined the relationship between fake news on social media and individuals’ conformity to its ideas through two studies. The first study included 3 experimental conditions in which participants were exposed to fake news social media posts. In the first condition, these posts included comments from social media users that expressed support for the information. The second condition included fake social media posts with comments that expressed disbelief or the acknowledgement of the post as fake news. The third condition included both types of comments: supportive and critical. The findings of this study indicated that the comments from other social media users influenced the likelihood that participants would share and/or comment on the posts. The second study was designed similarly to the first study but included a condition with no comments and another condition where there was a warning from the social media platform about the possible inaccuracy of the information. Based on the results of the second study, Colliander (2019) states, “Social media users seem to use the comments of other people as a guide for how to respond to disinformation online rather than disclaimers.” This finding emphasizes the significant impacts of social influence on beliefs and perceptions of information, even false information. 
	A study published in 2021 by Michael and Breaux aimed to examine whether political affiliation has an impact on the perception of fake news. Three almost identical studies were conducted, one in 2017, the second in 2018, and the last in 2020. Researchers hypothesized that people would trust news that agreed with their beliefs, and distrust news that disagreed with their beliefs. Participants were given a list of news sources and asked to rate them based on level of trustworthiness using the categories “real news,” “fake news,” and “propaganda.” Participants were also asked to define the terms “real news,” “fake news,” and “propaganda.” Researchers grouped participants based on “self-reported political identification.” (Michael & Breaux, 2021) The results of the study suggest that in general, more conservative people would view the news sources included in this study as less trustworthy than more liberal people. The two additional studies yielded similar results although there were some changes in the results due to the passage of time. Overall, researchers found that news sources that were rated as more trustworthy by liberals were likely to be rated as “fake news”/” propaganda” by conservatives and vice versa. Steps were taken to rule out level of familiarity as an explanation for perceived trustworthiness of the news sources. The findings of this study raise questions surrounding the influence of political groups on media consumption among the general public. Personal belief systems evolve over time partly due to the consumption of new information, therefore, with a high level of information absorption among individuals in society due to the current prevalent use of social media, it is important to acknowledge the influence of political ideologies on the acceptance and sharing of information. 
	Allen and colleagues (2020) argued that the spread of fake news may not be an urgent crisis due to the actual prevalence of this type of media compared to other media types. Through their research study, they sought to understand the prevalence of fake news based on the ideas that people use various platforms to consume media and that there is a high variety of types of media and news content. In order to do this, they measured TV consumption and consumption of media through desktop and mobile devices. They found that on average, Americans spend over 7.5 hours per day consuming media (Allen et al., 2020). The results also demonstrated that news constitutes only a fraction of individuals’ total daily media consumption, therefore, fake news must constitute a tiny fraction (about one tenth). Researchers noted that according to Google Scholar, between 2017 and 2020, 2210 English publications with “fake news” in the title emerged, while before this there were only 73. Although fake news is not widespread when compared to total media consumption, the increasing magnitude of the conversation surrounding it is enough to constitute an issue. 
	In conclusion, societal influences have a huge impact on personal values, beliefs, perceptions, and ideas. Social media is a new way that this has been occurring over the last ~25 years. Social media is the perfect tool for spreading misinformation over a large audience. This is why it is so important to acknowledge, identify, and fight the spread of fake news, other misleading propaganda and inaccurate information. To the naked eye, it might seem as though fake news is easy to avoid and will not become a huge problem. However, based on the research, fake news is not always as easy to reject as one might expect. As a society, we need to learn to be cautious among the constant flood of information that we are being exposed to.

Social Constructs in Modern-Day Society
Do all sociologists interpret social constructs such as religion and racism in similar ways? Since these topics can be abstract and there are many ways of viewing them, sociologists often disagree. However, they also agree on the implications of some of these social institutions. In Yuval Noah Harari’s book, 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, he explores many different problems which he sees to be the most relevant for today’s dynamic society. In this essay, I will specifically be focusing on his chapters about religion and immigration. I plan to compare them with a piece from Émile Durkheim and one by Patricia Hill Collins. 
Religion is a topic that many sociologists have explored. They try to determine why religion was a unifier, specifically in primeval societies. They also explore the trajectory that religion took and how it came to play the role it does today. Émile Durkheim is a French sociologist from the late 19th century-early 20th century who is considered to be one of the founders of modern-day sociology. In one of his papers, The Cultural Logic of Collective Representations, he explored how religion was developed. His main argument to explain the development of religion is that it was a way to unify groups of similar people to form a collective consciousness. Collective consciousness is an idea developed by Émile Durkheim and is defined as, “a group or society’s commonly shared fundamental beliefs, customs, norms, and values” (Bell). 
	Durkheim talks about how religion was essential to societies forming because they needed something to believe in. When societies were first forming, they revolved entirely around religion. In the collective consciousness, the ideas or beliefs that are unique to a certain group are called the collective representations. They help differentiate people’s identities. Since religion became the foundation of these collective consciousnesses, all of the collective representations in each society were tied to the religion that they believed in. Durkheim argues that without religion, society would not exist, and he believes that religion is essential for its functioning. He says that the collective consciousness of a group provides the group members with stability. When someone is surrounded with people who have similar beliefs, then they feel supported, so it is easier for them to see these beliefs as the truth. Religion became the foundation for all the important social institutions within a society, so Durkheim’s main idea when writing this piece is that society and religion are heavily intertwined. 
In the chapter about religion, Yuval Noah Harari discusses the uses of religion in the past versus the present. He acknowledges that religion used to play a big part in society, but its hold on people’s lives has loosened since it is not relevant to important aspects of life such as medicine, science, and economics. In the past, when people’s lives revolved around religion, it did control these fields. However, as knowledge adapts and we learn more about the world around us, religion becomes increasingly insignificant. In short, Harari’s argument is that although religion still has the power to unify and divide people, it is no longer necessary for our sense of community nor for us to develop as a society. He asserts that religion is essentially worthless in today’s society.
Although they have different takes on religion, both authors make good points. Durkheim focuses on the past and why religion came to play such an important role while Harari explores the present functions of religion. Harari makes good points about why religion is not as important and does not have as much power over people’s lives, but it seems like he allows some of his biases to seep into his writing. He calls religion a problem and says that it cannot be part of the solution. While some religious practices are problematic and have the tendency to ostracize people, they still have a way of gathering people together. In the midst of tragedy and despair, many people turn to the gods they believe in for hope. Most religious rituals include an aspect of community, or they bring people together, so I would argue that the positive impact religion has on people’s lives outweighs the negatives. This is not to disregard the negative experiences that people have had with religion. Instead, it is to offer a more neutral view that considers multiple perspectives. 
	One topic that was discussed in class is racism and how people are treated based on their unchangeable characteristics. Patricia Hill Collins wrote The Matrix of Domination. In it, she explained how people are either oppressed or oppressors based on their situation. She also argues how people can exist in both of these positions depending on the system of oppression. For example, a black man could be oppressed because of his race, but also be an oppressor because of his gender. She argues that the way people experience oppression and fit into the matrix of domination is very fluid and is subject to changes. The systemic level that racism functions on is one of the main factors in how the dominant group maintains control. On this level, social institutions such as schools or churches will only expose people to the ideas of their group, and they encourage thinking that coincides with their own. These institutions also require people who are not in the dominant group to be submissive, and they discourage any media that challenges their rhetoric. This essentially means that the dominant group often uses its power to continually oppress the submissive group.
	The chapter that Harari wrote on immigration ties in well with Collins’ argument. He talks about how people are treated differently in various cultures because of their appearance. He uses immigration as the primary example of this and goes into multiple debates surrounding this issue. The debates primarily revolve around immigrants assimilating to a country. For example, how much should immigrants have to assimilate. Or, at what point have they fully assimilated and can then be considered citizens? The anti-immigrant side argues that immigrants should have to assimilate to all aspects of European culture, but they also believe that Europe should not let in too many immigrants for fear that they are intolerant. They say that their society cannot manage an abundance of illiberal people. Some will even go as far to say that national community is the most important European value, so immigrants should go as far as to change their culture. This is where the debate of when someone fully assimilates comes into play. There still lies the question of what extent do immigrants need to go to if they want to become full citizens of a country. Some would argue that they have to change everything about themselves and their beliefs while the pro-immigration side would favor a faster acceptance. Nonetheless, it still takes a long time for immigrants to be considered a part of society instead of outsiders, and are they really ever fully accepted by the people they are surrounded by?
He concludes this chapter by discussing the switch from racism to culturism and how they are similar yet different forms of oppression. Historically, racism was more biologically based, so people were treated differently because of their DNA and their physical appearance, but it has evolved to be more a reflection on the places they are from. Harari says that the degrading comments people make about people of color are more about their culture instead of their biology. This is how the term culturism came to be. Since there is so much variation between cultures, they are the root of the differences in humans. He also discusses how their standing in a country change how they are treated. Regardless of political party, people often find immigrants to be a threat. Not only are they seen as outsiders, but many people also believe that they came to take something from them. Despite there being no real evidence to support this claim, it still instills a negative attitude toward immigrants. When immigrants are portrayed as a threat or as the other, then citizens of the country are more likely to react badly when encountering them. It also subjects immigrants to higher rates of racism. 
Collins’ theory that someone can be an oppressor, oppressed, or function on both levels depending on the situation can be applied to immigration. Although Harari and Collins do not have the exact same argument in their writings, their ideas are complementary. On one hand, Collins talks about the different levels that racism can exist on, and she discusses the implications of the institution that is perpetuating the racism. On the other hand, I would argue that Harari uses immigration as an example of the different functions of racism. Instead of directly stating how immigrants suffer from the racist ideas and actions that are perpetuated against them, he describes the tension surrounding immigration and discusses the effects of it. His explanation of culturism, or modern-day racism that focuses more on a person’s culture than their biology, directly correlates to Collins’ theory. For example, if a Muslim man immigrated to England, then he would most likely face hate, exclusion, and oppression from the people who live there. Alternatively, if an American man immigrated to somewhere with high populations of Muslims in the Middle East, he would be seen as a threat and untrustworthy. The Muslim man would then occupy the position of an oppressor instead of the oppressed. Therefore, one person could be both oppressed and an oppressor depending on the situation.
Whether religion is still important or has become a trivial institution is something that sociologists could debate. There is strong evidence for it being essential in the past, but Harari believes that the past is where it should stay. For this reason, Harari and Durkheim’s arguments are contradictory. However, the one concept that most sociologists can agree on is racism and that it is still a problem on a global scale. Both Harari and Collins give examples of how it is still present and creates injustices for the oppressed, but neither offers a solution. Their arguments have the same basis, so they are complimentary. All three writers offered good support for their conclusion and make a strong argument in favor of their position. Now, it is up to us to determine what we see to be the truth.

George Herbert Mead’s concept of the self is a challenge to itself as according to Mead the self is not inherent to itself and is its own unique set of characteristics and experiences that separate itself from one’s body. The Self vs Body is one of the key aspects of his philosophy as the Self relies on the physical aspect while the latter does not rely on the former. With the body being the propulsion or machine for the self, it is not unlike how the body would be the stage for Erving Goffman’s principles. 
One of the most important aspects of the self in Mead’s eye is similar to Cooley’s “looking glass self” where in individuals imagine how others perceive them and adjust their self-concept, accordingly, usually based on the specific group. Though this pails in comparison to his primary point of language or communication, individuals learn to interpret symbols and meanings within their cultural context, contributing to the ongoing development of the self. The fluidity of oneself, according to Mead, arises from the continuous negotiation and reinterpretation of social experiences, shaping our identities and our lifespan. Though the main issues of Mead’s philosophy come in that he hardly provides any notion of how emotions and conflict shape one’s personality rather than focusing on the language and group setting even so his persuasive argument is compelling.
This is all further supported by Erving Goffman's dramaturgical approach which complements Mead's ideas by portraying social life as something akin to a theatrical performance with how we as the actors play roles in settings, people must navigate through life’s many different social situations by portraying aspects of their identity deemed appropriate for the context such as how one would seem studious and observant around a teacher while acting more of oneself and relaxed around close friends at recess. This self-presentation shows how fluid oneself, as individuals actively move to conform to societal expectations while navigating the intricate social stage though, this is not so true in every case as the stage is divided into a fore-and-back where one shows different levels of who they truly are. 
One of the faults of Goffman’s view as it does not account for how social media affects one’s performance as people fake their backstage view and spew out a highly curated slop of a front stage with social media not being a truly collective work where people can build and react off one another as they would. Making this an empty husk of oneself.

If their ideas are well-received, and they successfully integrate they may act one way or if it is seen negatively, they will adjust their behavior to fit in more appropriately. While Goffman’s work would be more suited for day-to-day actions this comes up most apparently within meetings as one has to manage to appear professional, choosing what and when to say things. This strategic self-presentation is influenced by the desire to be perceived as competent, cooperative, and aligned with organizational goals. The dynamic nature reflects the fluidity of the self as individuals adapt their self to fit the social concept circle setting.
